 the blood keeps walking?

00:08:03.680 --> 00:08:08.680
 But anyway, all these papers on it and cadavers were drained.

00:08:08.680 --> 00:08:11.360
 And there was a lot of people dying suddenly

00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:13.360
 in the 1920s in Russia as well.

00:08:13.360 --> 00:08:14.680
 (laughing)

00:08:14.680 --> 00:08:16.680
 Over in America, there was another interesting

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:20.560
 frontline character, which was Charles Drew,

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:25.120
 amazing character, Drew, drew a lot of blood himself

00:08:25.120 --> 00:08:27.640
 over his lifetime because he came up

00:08:27.640 --> 00:08:31.160
 with large-scale blood banks in World War II,

00:08:31.160 --> 00:08:33.480
 but he was also African-American,

00:08:33.480 --> 00:08:38.120
 and this really limited him from quite a lot of access

00:08:38.120 --> 00:08:40.400
 to medical places in the States.

00:08:40.400 --> 00:08:43.800
 - Yeah, yeah, and what I read about Drew,

00:08:43.800 --> 00:08:45.680
 and I don't know, this may be apocryphal,

00:08:45.680 --> 00:08:47.960
 but what I read was that at the end of his life,

00:08:47.960 --> 00:08:51.400
 he actually needed blood, but at that time,

00:08:51.400 --> 00:08:54.080
 if you were black, you couldn't get white blood.

00:08:54.080 --> 00:08:58.320
 There was this segregation in blood transfusion.

00:08:58.320 --> 00:09:01.960
 - Fortunately, that wasn't the case,

00:09:01.960 --> 00:09:03.560
 specifically with him.

00:09:03.560 --> 00:09:06.440
 It was the case that that is how blood transfusions

00:09:06.440 --> 00:09:08.600
 were working in America at the time,

00:09:08.600 --> 00:09:11.320
 but he was really mangled up in a car crash,

00:09:11.320 --> 00:09:13.680
 and unfortunately, nothing would have saved him.

